explanation:
- UT_GetStubEntry (prototype): Needed to confirm how FuncKey is passed (by value or by pointer) and to ensure the call does not take the address of the parameter or otherwise cause the handler function to modify the local parameter variable.
- UT_SetVaHandlerFunction (prototype): Needed to verify how DefaultHandler and FuncKey are passed into that function (by value or by pointer) so we can determine whether UT_ExecuteVaHandler’s parameter variables could be modified indirectly.
- UT_DefaultStubImplWithArgs (prototype): Required to check how FunctionName, FuncKey and VaList are accepted (by value or by pointer) and whether passing VaList copies or shares internal state on the target platform (see va_list ABI).
- UT_EntryKey_t (typedef/definition): Knowing the underlying type of FuncKey (integer, pointer, struct, etc.) is necessary to judge whether passing it to callees could allow modification of the caller’s parameter object or pointer value.
- UT_VaHandlerFunc_t (typedef/definition): Needed to know whether DefaultHandler is a pointer type and whether it is passed or modified as a pointer-to-pointer in callees.
- va_list (definition for target platform/ABI): va_list can be an array or pointer type depending on ABI; its semantics (copied by value or effectively reference-like) determine whether passing VaList to UT_DefaultStubImplWithArgs could modify the caller’s va_list object and thus whether the parameter variable is being modified.
- UT_ENTRYTYPE_FINAL_HANDLER (macro/enum): Included to confirm it is a plain constant and that the UT_GetStubEntry call uses only value arguments (no hidden address-of operations via macro expansions).

These symbols and prototypes let an analyzer determine whether parameters are passed only by value inside UT_ExecuteVaHandler or whether any callee could modify the parameter variables (violating the MISRA rule).
